{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657669"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:32:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:32:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20590"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20590"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13467"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93762"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13467"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20590"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76972"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"12504"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12797"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32161"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32630"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93762"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 3-year-old child presents with a five-day history of high fever, bilateral non-exudative conjunctivitis, red cracked lips, and a polymorphous rash. The child also has cervical lymphadenopathy and swelling of the hands and feet. Echocardiography shows mild dilation of the coronary arteries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following histopathological findings is most characteristic of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Segmental thrombosing vasculitis","Granulomatous inflammation with giant cells","Neutrophilic infiltration with fibrinoid necrosis","Eosinophilic infiltration with extravascular granulomas","Lymphocytic vasculitis with endothelial hyperplasia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is classic for Kawasaki disease, an acute febrile vasculitis of childhood. The histopathological hallmark of Kawasaki disease is \u003Cstrong\u003Eneutrophilic infiltration with fibrinoid necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E of the vessel walls. This inflammatory process primarily affects medium-sized arteries, with the coronary arteries being particularly vulnerable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESegmental thrombosing vasculitis\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of thromboangiitis obliterans (Buerger disease), which typically affects young adult smokers and involves small to medium-sized peripheral vessels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatous inflammation with giant cells\u003C/strong\u003E is typically seen in giant cell arteritis or granulomatosis with polyangiitis, conditions that rarely affect young children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophilic infiltration with extravascular granulomas\u003C/strong\u003E is the hallmark of eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis (formerly Churg-Strauss syndrome), which is characterized by asthma, eosinophilia, and vasculitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphocytic vasculitis with endothelial hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E is more consistent with conditions like cutaneous lymphocytic vasculitis or some forms of collagen vascular disease, not Kawasaki disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKawasaki disease progresses through several phases: acute (1-2 weeks) with neutrophilic infiltration, subacute (2-4 weeks) with mononuclear cell infiltration, and chronic (\u003E40 days) with fibrosis and scarring. The most serious complication is coronary artery aneurysm formation, which occurs in approximately 25% of untreated cases and can lead to myocardial infarction, ischemic heart disease, or sudden death.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Kawasaki disease is an acute, febrile vasculitis primarily affecting medium-sized arteries, particularly the coronary arteries.","The histopathological hallmark of Kawasaki disease is neutrophilic infiltration of vessel walls with subsequent fibrinoid necrosis.","Kawasaki disease predominantly affects children under 5 years of age and is a leading cause of acquired heart disease in children."],"references":["Mitchell RN, Halushka MK. Blood vessels. In: Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, editors. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. p. 485\u2013525."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76972"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20590"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76972"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-22T10:04:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-22T10:08:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13467"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93762"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4914"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Blood ves